  <h1 class="hidetitle">Minimalist Design <br />for Space Camera Flight Software</h1> 
  <h2>Embedded spaceflight software: Small is beautiful.</h2> 
  <h3>Michael Caplinger</h3> 
  <p>This article discusses more than 35 years of experience with writing small software systems that control spaceflight imaging instruments, usually simply called <i>cameras</i>. We make no claim that any of the methods we use at Malin Space Science Systems are at all unique or unusual; most of them are certainly reflected in a whole range of embedded software programs for applications as diverse as household appliances, consumer electronics, industrial control systems, Internet of Things hardware, and vehicles.</p> 
  <p>Unlike the apparently natural trajectory of software toward larger and more complex systems, this article advocates for a "small is beautiful" minimalist approach, describes some of the costs of complexity, and gives some examples of minimalist systems that have performed well in practice over decades of use.</p> 
  <p>The guiding principle in this work was brilliantly articulated by the British computer scientist C. A. R. "Tony" Hoare in his Turing Award lecture in 1980:</p> 
  <blockquote>
    ...there are two ways of constructing a software design: One way is to make it so simple that there are obviously no deficiencies and the other way is to make it so complicated that there are no obvious deficiencies. The first method is far more difficult. It demands the same skill, devotion, insight, and even inspiration as the discovery of the simple physical laws which underlie the complex phenomena of nature. It also requires a willingness to accept objectives which are limited by physical, logical, and technological constraints, and to accept a compromise when conflicting objectives cannot be met. No committee will ever do this until it is too late. 
  </blockquote> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Attributes of flight software</h3> 
  <p>Flight software is similar to other small embedded software systems but with two additional challenges:</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Criticality.</i></b> The software has to operate without significant error for long periods of time and ideally not require any human intervention for fault recovery. That said, instruments are typically not mission critical, so the worst-case outcome for a fault is restricted to science data loss, a small amount of which might be deemed acceptable.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i> Radiation tolerance.</i></b> Typically, electronic systems in space suffer from radiation-induced "single event upsets," which might cause bits in processor registers and memories to change state spontaneously. (Hardware immune to these effects is typically too resource hungry or expensive to use in instruments and is reserved for more mission-critical uses.) While there are known software methods to address this problem (for example, use of error-correcting codes or majority voting of multiple redundant circuits), these are resource intensive and are often omitted or weakened if the resulting windows of vulnerability are not too large.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Functions</h4> 
  <p>Camera flight software typically performs several functions, including:</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Management of data flow from camera hardware into memory buffers.</i></b> This is often performed by hardware because of the high speed of raw pixel data transfer, but software is usually required to set up transfers, start the imaging process, and perform buffer space allocation.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Time synchronization and tagging.</i></b> It's important for analysis to know when images are taken. On most missions, there is a single spacecraft clock whose value must be distributed to instruments and kept in sync.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Data compression.</i></b> Raw image data is voluminous and the downlink data rate can be limited, so some form of image data compression is often used. Depending on speed requirements, this can be done purely in software or by a mixture of hardware and software resources.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Command interpretation.</i></b> Commands from the spacecraft are usually at a high level of abstraction and need to be translated into specific camera hardware settings.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i> Data protocol construction.</i></b> Instrument data interfaces typically rely on some kind of standardized formatting—the Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems (CCSDS) Space Packet Protocol,<sup>2</sup> for example—that uses small packets with headers and checksums to assure data integrity and add ancillary data such as timestamps. These protocols often apply in both directions, so software must strip the protocol on input and apply it on output as needed.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Memory management.</i></b> Many instruments have large internal memory buffers—volatile or nonvolatile or both—that can store multiple images. These buffers have to be allocated and freed as needed as operations proceed.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Command sequencing.</i></b> Some instruments are autonomous and may acquire multiple images over the course of hours or days, either according to a regular but adjustable schedule or via time-tagged commands sent from the ground.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Image parameter adjustments.</i></b> Some cameras have autofocus and/or autoexposure capabilities that compute image parameters from the actual imaging conditions.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Higher-level data processing.</i></b> Image processing, feature recognition, focus merging, and image registration are functions that can be done by software.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Our first experience—Mars Observer Camera</h3> 
  <p>My first experience with flight software development was for the Mars Observer Camera (MOC).<sup>5</sup> The MOC used a 32-bit microprocessor: the Sandia SA3330,<sup>3</sup> a radiation-hardened version of the National Semiconductor 32C016 processor. Camera data flow was managed by four custom gate arrays, and the system had a 12MB DRAM buffer, 192KB of SRAM, and 128KB of EPROM.</p> 
  <p>The software was all written in C. It consisted of about 17,000 source lines of code (SLOC), roughly evenly split between a small custom-developed realtime kernel and application-specific image processing and data compression functions.</p> 
  <p>The kernel used a preemptive stack-based model of execution based on multiple interrupt priorities. Once a task started, it had to run to completion but could be interrupted by a task triggered by a higher-priority interrupt. The kernel provided a dynamic data allocation mechanism using a linked-list data structure to store variable-length records. The system featured a clever "virtual camera" function that could store multiple images at different resolutions from the wide-angle cameras simultaneously. Error-correcting codes for DRAM were implemented in software using hardware-computed syndromes for image data. The system could store several weeks' worth of image commands in a DRAM buffer. The hardware provided a watchdog timer mechanism that could warm-start the processor if the software failed to update it, and the DRAM command buffer would survive such a reset, losing only the commands for a few hours' worth of operation.</p> 
  <p>While, ultimately, the MOC was a great success<sup>6</sup> and the software, in general, performed as expected, it had two significant issues. The first, which occurred late in development, was an interaction between complexity, test phasing, and schedule. The software had been designed and implemented by a three-person team, but largely owing to schedule slippage in hardware development, that team left the project shortly after they completed the first flight build. The second only became obvious during integrated system testing, which revealed that resource usage of the dynamic memory allocation was hard to predict, and the system often ran out of resources when executing realistic command sequences. These problems were addressed by surgical changes to reduce dynamic memory usage in a few key areas. There were also a number of bugs associated with the complex interrupt and priority scheme that were difficult to track down. More than 40 bug fixes were made between the first flight build and the version ultimately flown.</p> 
  <p>After arriving on Mars, the system experienced fairly frequent spontaneous reboots. While a complete understanding of the root cause was never reached before the end of the mission, all evidence suggested that the reboots were a result of bit flips in the processor registers causing corruption of the linked-list memory structures. This corruption led to endless traversal of the linked list and subsequent watchdog timer expiration and reboot. Ironically, although we had made a significant effort to use a "rad-hard" processor, the SA3300 had a fairly low upset threshold,<sup>9</sup> making the use of complex data structures without substantial additional error checking unwise.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Design principles</h3> 
  <p>After the MOC experience, we incorporated several design principles into the development process for new software:</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Minimize or eliminate interrupt usage.</i></b> Without interrupts, there is never any nondeterministic alteration of control flow and no need for critical sections or any other multithreading mechanism. Reasoning about the software's behavior (via loop invariants, for example) is comparatively straightforward.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Use a single thread of execution.</i></b> A typical system will have a simple outer loop checking for command receipt, will then execute a received command, and might execute housekeeping functions periodically based on the value of an internal clock.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Use polling instead of interrupts for hardware interfaces. </i></b>Since the software is single threaded, waiting for a single hardware operation to complete is done with a simple polling loop, typically deep in the call graph in the function invoking the hardware operation. If there are multiple sources that all need to be polled in rapid succession, it might be necessary to restructure the code so the outermost loop is continually polling for event completion and updating control block structures accordingly.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Minimize use of dynamic memory allocation.</i></b> Most memory use cases can be handled with simple fixed-size tables, and these are much easier to reason about and track the usage of.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Push back on nonessential requirements. </i></b>For example, one customer wanted the system to send health telemetry on one-second centers continuously. It was unclear why, since they weren't implementing any form of fault response and didn't need to know that the instrument was healthy on such a fine timescale, but it seemed to be a matter of tradition. We could have implemented this functionality, but only by using a timer interrupt or a hardware implementation. Ultimately, we were able to convince the customer simply to be satisfied with less frequent health telemetry, with small time gaps while other command execution was active when telemetry was scheduled.</p> 
  <p>• <b><i>Rely on hardware for essential realtime response.</i></b> In those cases where immediate response is required, it is often simpler for the overall system to have hardware produce the response, with some non-time-critical interaction with the software as needed. Since FPGA designs allow flexible hardware definition, this is easy enough to implement, at least for simple behaviors.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Case studies</h3> 
  <h4>Mars Science Laboratory Mastcam</h4> 
  <p>As an example of this philosophy, consider the software we wrote for the Mastcam instrument on the Mars Science Laboratory (MSL) rover.<sup>7</sup> This software runs on an embedded Microblaze processor in the instrument's Xilinx FPGA; the processor runs at 40MHz and has access to 128KB of internal SRAM, a 128MB DRAM buffer, and 8GB of NAND flash memory. It is responsible for receiving commands from the rover, acquiring images from the camera hardware, controlling the camera's focus and filter wheel mechanisms, supervising the hardware-based image compression logic, implementing a simple file system in the flash memory, and transmitting raw or compressed image data to the rover. </p> 
  <p>In addition, it performs "Z-stacking," a computer-vision?based focus merging operation on images taken with the rover's microscopic camera (essentially a macro lens with adjustable focus). The entire code volume is about 4,600 SLOC, of which about a quarter is the Z-stacking. </p> 
  <p>This software has been operating on Mars without modification since MSL landed in 2012.</p> 
  <p>The main loop of the software is extremely simple:</p> 
  <p><code> main() { <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;init(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;while(1) { <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;if(cmd_recv(0)) { <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;cmd_execute(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;} <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;periodic(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;} <br />} </code></p> 
  <p>where any hardware polling is done deep within the call tree of <code>cmd_execute</code>. Outside of that function, all of the hardware is idle and <code>cmd_recv</code> simply polls the receiver logic to check for new commands, while any periodic functions are done within <code>periodic</code> (all such functions must take only a small amount of time to execute).</p> 
  <p>The radiation environment on the Martian surface is relatively benign. There have been one or two instances of data corruption caused by radiation, but, in general, the software has never seen a major reset. Typically, the instrument is powered and operating for only a few hours per Martian day, with the rover in hibernation state at night. To date, the Mastcams alone have returned more than 400,000 images.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Lunar Reconnaissance Orbit Camera</h4> 
  <p>The Lunar Reconnaissance Orbit Camera (LROC) instrument has three cameras: two copies of the narrow angle camera (NAC) and a wide-angle multispectral camera (WAC). The Sequence and Control System (SCS) sits between these cameras and the spacecraft with which it communicates by way of a single bidirectional Spacewire link.<sup>8</sup> The SCS hardware has a Xilinx FPGA with an embedded Microblaze processor but has no external memory; a double buffer for the small WAC images is implemented in internal FPGA RAM.</p> 
  <p>Most processing functions are performed by FPGA logic, with the SCS software sequencing a small number of atomic hardware operations: Take a NAC image, take a WAC image, read out a NAC or WAC image buffer segment with optional compression. NAC image segments stream directly though the logic without being touched by software. The SCS also receives commands from the spacecraft and manages an internal time base.</p> 
  <p>Since most of the functions are done in logic, the SCS software is quite small (about 600 SLOC). Its main loop is an example of inverted polling:</p> 
  <p><code> main() { <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;init(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;while(1) { <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;check_xmit(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;while(cmd_recv()) cmd_execute(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;wac_do_boot(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;wac_start(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;wac_read(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;wac_xmit(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;nac_start(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;nac_xmit(); <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;} <br />} </code></p> 
  <p>where each function polls for the completion of a particular logic operation as needed. Each function maintains its current state as needed in a per-camera control data structure.</p> 
  <p>The radiation environment in lunar orbit causes an SCS hardware upset roughly once a week. Fault recovery is done autonomously via two mechanisms: First, the spacecraft cycles power if the SCS fails to respond to a request for status; second, the spacecraft cycles power during inactive periods roughly once a day to clear any faults that were not so severe as to cause a failure to respond.</p> 
  <p>LROC has been a tremendous success: Since arriving in lunar orbit in 2009, it has returned more than 2.3 million NAC images, mapped more than 98 percent of the lunar surface, and produced 1.74 petabytes and more than 3.9 million observations for NASA's Planetary Data System.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Touch-and-Go Camera System</h4> 
  <p>The Touch-and-Go Camera System (TAGCAMS) on the OSIRIS-REx asteroid sample return mission has three 5-megapixel visible camera heads (two monochrome for navigation and one color to monitor the exterior of the sample return capsule.<sup>1</sup> These cameras are controlled by two copies of the digital video recorder (DVR), which host the instrument flight software. This software runs on an embedded Microblaze processor in the DVR's Xilinx FPGA; the processor runs at 50MHz and has 128KB of SRAM for program and data storage and an 8GB NAND flash buffer, but no additional DRAM storage. While the software was initially derived from the MSL software, significant changes had to be made to operate within the severely limited memory footprint.</p> 
  <p>The software is implemented in about 3,000 SLOC. It uses the standard loop structure with polling for completion of camera image reception embedded within the camera functions; this polling is done on a 4K flash page fill basis. The spacecraft data interface consists of a low-speed bidirectional asynchronous line for commands and status telemetry and a unidirectional synchronous serial line to send raw or compressed image data. A single interrupt is used on receipt of asynchronous characters, since the logic implementation of the UART (universal asynchronous receiver-transmitter) has a very small input buffer, and characters would otherwise be lost if the interface was not polled while other operations were being performed. A circular buffer is used so that interrupt masking is never required.</p> 
  <p>The radiation environment in interplanetary space causes an upset to the system roughly every two to three days. The software is reset by the logic watchdog timer if it is not serviced, and the spacecraft routinely resets the system once a day during inactive periods.</p> 
  <p>Over the course of the OSIRIS-REx mission, TAGCAMS returned more than 32,000 images and was a key component of the mission's successful capture and subsequent return to Earth of a sample of the asteroid Bennu.<sup>4</sup></p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Conclusion</h3> 
  <p>This article has described software principles that have resulted in systems that have been implemented on time and within budget and have gone on to perform well in flight on more than a dozen missions to date. We are currently writing software for several future missions. One of these is for NASA's Dragonfly mission, which will put these principles into service on the surface of Saturn's moon Titan in 2034. While acknowledging that these examples are far less complex than many aerospace software projects, we argue that all such systems can benefit from a minimalist viewpoint to the extent possible.</p> 
